When going from properties to category talk about ATL semantic hub¶

1. Introduction¶

Artificial Neural Networks have proved themselves to be very powerful tools in performing tasks (namely classification) on raw data. As an example on the ImageNet dataset, modern neural network models have reached 01% Top-1 accuracy for classification (https://paperswithcode.com/sota/image-classification-on-imagenet). However, what these models learn that is enabling them to perform so well is mostly still a mystery.

It's clear that for us human beings, even though we have unique concepts for each type of entity, we still group entities together not only based on obvious taxonomic similarities (for example lions and tigers are both "cats") but also based on properties. For example, dogs and cats are more similar than dogs and birds not just because the first pair are taxonomically similar (both mammals), but they are more similar because they share many properties and attributes (and arguably this is the source of the taxonomic distinction). Dogs and Cats both: have 4 legs, have fur, have tails, etc. Though it may seem obvious that these are true of most mammals, when first seeing these animals it's already clear that they are more similar than the pair "dog and bird" despite not knowing what "mammal" means. So although our semantic knowledge may be organized in a symbolic taxonomy as we mature, initially that cannot be the case since we learn from the raw data presented by the world and not through symbolic manipulation representing entities in the world.

Following this line of reasoning,

WordNet Tree vs ANN

So if that is the case, what happens when neural networks are trained on properties and attributes of categories instead of the named categories themselves? Do the networks representations reflect similarties in properties between inputs? Do the differentiation dynamics between types reflect human knowledge about the categorization of these entities? Can we reconstruct entites based on properties? These are some of the questions I aim to explore in this analysis.

Motivation¶

To get an idea of what has just tbeen described above, let's look at an example.

In this example, we're going to be exploring the differentiation dynamics of a very simple neual network. We will look at a few natural language sentences of entities and their properties and see how the networks entity representation changes as training progresses. Entities are mapped to attributes/properties via predicates.

This is a reimplementation of the paper linked here: https://www.nature.com/articles/nrn1076. Note: The idea for the example was reimplemented from the paper, but the code was written by me.

This function will then be used to map each of the items in the lists to one-hot encoded vectors, so that we can use the vectors to learn mappings between the entities, relations, and attributes.

In [171]:
def make_vectors(list_of_xs):
    x_to_vectors = {}
    
    vectors = np.eye(len(list_of_xs)).astype(np.float32)
    
    for index, x in enumerate(list_of_xs):
        x_to_vectors[x] = vectors[index]
        
    return x_to_vectors

This creates the one-hot encoded vectors for the entities, relations, and attributes.

In [172]:
items_to_vectors = make_vectors(items)
relations_to_vectors = make_vectors(relations)
attributes_to_vectors = make_vectors(attributes)

In order to learn mappings, we have to create propositions that involve the appropriate entity-relation-attribute connections. So to do that I create a list of propositions in natural language which will serve as the training exmaples for the neural network.

This function takes a list of natural language propositions and returns a list of tuples of the one-hot encoded version of the proposition. Here the input is the entity and relation and the output is the attribute. More explicitly, we are leanring a {(entity, relation) -> attribute} mapping. Since this function uses a look up, it does not work with words not in the lists created above.

In [174]:
def parse_propositions(propositions):
    parsed_propositions = []
    
    for proposition in propositions:
        proposition_parts = proposition.split()
        
        targets = np.zeros(len(attributes))
        
        for part in proposition_parts[2:]:
            targets += attributes_to_vectors[part.replace(',', '')]
            
        item = items_to_vectors[proposition_parts[0]]
        relation = relations_to_vectors[proposition_parts[1]]
        
        
        parsed_propositions.append(((item, relation), targets))
        
    return parsed_propositions
In [175]:
learning_data = parse_propositions(propositions)

Here we create the neural network that will use the training examples above to learn representations of the entities based on the relations and constrained by the attributes. The layer design (2 hidden, 1 output) follows the design in the paper above.

In [176]:
class semantic_network(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, num_items, num_relations, num_attributes):
        super(semantic_network, self).__init__()
        
        self.item_to_rep = nn.Linear(num_items, num_items)
        self.combine = nn.Linear(num_items + num_relations, num_items + num_relations)
        self.complete_query = nn.Linear(num_items + num_relations, num_attributes)
        
    def forward(self, x):
        item = x[0]
        relation = x[1]
        representation = self.item_to_rep(item)
        hidden = self.combine(torch.cat((representation, relation), 0))
        out = self.complete_query(hidden)

        return out, representation
In [177]:
model = semantic_network(8, 4, len(attributes))
In [178]:
epochs = 2000
learning_rate = 0.01

lossfunction = nn.BCEWithLogitsLoss()
optimizer = optim.SGD(model.parameters(), lr=learning_rate)
In [179]:
for epoch in range (epochs):
    total_loss = 0
    #train loop
    for (item, relation), attribute in learning_data:
        (item, relation), attribute = (torch.from_numpy(item), torch.from_numpy(relation)), torch.from_numpy(attribute)
        #forward
        logits, representation = model((item, relation))
        
        #loss
        loss = lossfunction(logits, attribute)
        total_loss += loss.item()
        
        #backward
        optimizer.zero_grad()
        loss.backward()
        
        #update
        optimizer.step()
        
    if epoch % 200 == 0:
        print(f"Loss: {total_loss/len(learning_data)}")
        print()

As you can see it is very clear that the representations of things that we would as humans would count as similar are actually similar. After a single transformation from the one-hot encoded vector, the entities representations look similar to other entities like it. For example salmon has a very similar representation to sunfish, and the euclidean distance of pine and oak are very close as compared to pine (or oak) and any other category.























However, as mentioned above we as humans clearly do not learn in purely symbolic ways. So, in this analysis I will be looking at the use of raw images as input.























Questions¶






















I will explore what the differentiation dynamics are when we use raw images and properties as opposed to the 1 output category. I will compare that to the differentiation dynamics based on using the 1 output category, and will determine if this using this intermediate classification step will improve classification performance. In doing this we will be able to get a sense of whether augmenting a dataset with handcrafted intermediate features will boost the learning signal in classification tasks. This also may allow for the creation of algorithms that fail in more human like ways since we are restricting the ways that the classification algorithms can learn.


Questions:


    

  • Do differentiation dynamics differ between a property based target vs a class based target?
    • 

  • In what ways do the neural representations of the inputs cluster between classes?
    • 

  • Does augmenting a dataset with handcrated learning signals boost classification accuracy?
    • 

  • In what ways does a neural classifier fail when learning from properties vs learning from class?
    • 
























Data Curation/Augmentation/Exploration¶






















In this analysis we will be using the CIFAR10 dataset. The CIFAR-10 dataset is a dataset consisting of 60000 32x32 images distributed over 10 classes with 6000 images per class. I am using this dataset because it has a small number of classes making it reasonable to create natural language propositions for each class, and it will be reasonable to visualize and statiscally test the differences between the different classes. This dataset also has an even distribution of classes among the imagesmeaning no particular class will be biased over others. CIFAR-10: https://www.cs.toronto.edu/~kriz/cifar.html


To access the dataset, I will be using the torchvision.datasets library. I then transform the images into normalized tensors with range [-1, 1] so that it is easier for the network to learn.= by stabilizing the gradient, preventing it from growing it too large.

An initial investigation we can do is to look at the similarity of the images based on euclidean distance to determine if augmenting the data even initially makes sense. If images with more similar classes are already numerically similar then there would be no point in introducing more signal. To perform a quick comparison we will look use some of the images above.


We will compare two deer images and a deer with a dog image and a deer with a frog image.



















In [ ]:



     


# Choosing two deer images from above and calculating the image distance
deer1 = images[4].reshape(-1, 3*32*32)
deer2 = images[6].reshape(-1, 3*32*32)
print(f"Similarity between deer images: {((deer1-deer2)**2).sum()}")

# Choosing a dog image from above and calculating distance with one deer image
dog = images[5].reshape(-1, 3*32*32)
print(f"Similarity between deer and dog images: {((deer1-dog)**2).sum()}")

# Choosing a frog image from above and calculating distance with one deer image
frog = images[15].reshape(-1, 3*32*32)
print(f"Similarity between deer and frog images: {((deer1-frog)**2).sum()}")



     























As you can see using an image distance metric it's clear that, numerrical similarity between images is not enough to learn the kinds of similarities that were discussed above. Based on euclidean distance the frog and deer images were closest, then the dog and deer images, and lastly the deer and deer images. What we  would have wanted was (1) deer-deer (2) deer-dog (3) deer-frog, since based on properties that ranking reflects the pairs of entities that are most similar.























Next, we get right to creating the network that will learn based on properties as opposed to learning based on the class category. To do this we will use pytorch like above.



















In [73]:



     


class image_network(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, num_relations, num_attributes):
        super(image_network, self).__init__()
        
        
        self.image_to_rep = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Conv2d(3, 8, 3),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.MaxPool2d(2, 2),
            nn.Conv2d(8, 16, 3),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.MaxPool2d(2, 2),
            nn.Conv2d(16, 32, 3),
            nn.Flatten(),
            nn.Linear(512, 64)
        )
        
        self.combine = nn.Linear(64 + num_relations, 64 + num_relations)
        
        self.complete_query = nn.Linear(64 + num_relations, num_attributes)
        
    def forward(self, img, relation):
        representation = self.image_to_rep(img)
        hidden = self.combine(torch.cat((representation, torch.unsqueeze(relation, 0)), 1))
        out = self.complete_query(hidden)

        return out, representation

From the clustering analysis it's clear to see that our intuition about how the representations would cluster is correct. We believed that the neural network algorithm would learn to cluster images that are taxonomically similar, this seems to be the case. The vehicles are clustered together and the animals are clustered together. Within vehicles car and truck are closer, and within animals cat and dog are close. The only aspect of the clustering that does not match out intuition is very similar to bird and frog as opposed to horse, dog, or cat. This not only does not match our intution about how the classes should cluster, but it is also unexpected based on the attributes that deer has. Deer has attributes that are most similar to horse, so we expected that it would cluster closely with horse. It's unclear as to why this is happening.


Additionally, it looks like the representations for each of the classes also reflect the idea of taxonomic similarity. This way of visualizing the representations is much more opaque than the clustering analysis so we will not discuss it here any further.























So seeing those results a natural next question is whether or not this attribute based model actually performs better on classification tasks than a network trained only trained on classification. We may expect that since the attribute based network has learned these intermediate representations that it would be able to use that knowledge in order to make better classification predictions.


To test this we will usee transfer learning. We are going to utilize the convolutional part of the neural network and attach it to a new fully connected set of layers and train the network based on the original (unaugmented dataset). We will then compare the accuracy results of the attribute network with the results of a normal classification network.



















In [113]:



     


class image_network_classification(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super(image_network_classification, self).__init__()
        
        
        self.classification_head = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(64, 64),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(64, 32),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(32, 10)
        )
        
        
    def forward(self, img):
        representation = model.image_to_rep(img)
        out = self.classification_head(representation)

        return out

for epoch in range (epochs):
    total_loss = 0
    #train loop
    for image, label in tqdm(trainloader):

        logits = model_classifier(image)

        #loss
        loss = lossfunction(logits, label)
        total_loss += loss.item()

        #backward
        loss.backward()

        #update
        optimizer.step()
        optimizer.zero_grad()
        

    print(f"Loss: {total_loss/(len(trainloader))}")
    print()

Now that the net work has been trained for classification on the dataset, we will now test its performance by determining its accuracy on the testing data.



















In [135]:



     


second_guess = defaultdict(lambda: defaultdict(int))
correct = 0

with torch.no_grad():
    for image, label in testloader:
        logits = model_classifier(image)
        predicted_values, predicted_labels = torch.topk(logits.data, 2)
        #print(predicted_labels)
        first_class = index_to_items[label.item()]
        second_class = index_to_items[predicted_labels[0][1].item()]
        second_guess[first_class][second_class] += 1
        
        correct += (predicted_labels == label).sum().item()
        
print(f'Accuracy: {100 * (correct / len(testloader))}')



     






















    
    






Accuracy: 77.37




























Now that we have our models accuracy, we compare it to the accuracy of models that have been trained for classification on CIFAR-10 data. By looking at this: https://paperswithcode.com/sota/image-classification-on-cifar-10, it is clear that our attribute model does not perform as well as the top classification models. This could be attributed to many different factors including: model size, simplicity of architecture, etc. However, here we are more interested in how the network classifies. So to investigate this, we will look into the second best predictions the network made for the different images in the test set, and determine if it is making its second best guess based on taxonomic similarity.

From this it is clear to see that our network is working in ways that we would expect. For some of the classes, the second guesses are dominated by the class that was most similar to it in the clustering analysis. For example: second guesses for dog were dominated by cat, the same is true for car and truck, and ship and plane. One interesting note is that deer and horse are more evenly distributed than the other classes. However, despite this the seem to be obeying the taxonomy since most of their frequency falls with other living things.


Although this matches our intuition we will now perform a simple statistical test.


Here we use a chisquare frequency test to determine if the frequencies of the second guesses are significantly different from uniform.

Conclusion¶






















Our analysis above lead us to believe that utilizing taxonomic similarity (and more generally handcrated features) can play a role in neural network learning algorithms. Although the network did not perform as well as the top CIFAR-10 classification models, it did perform withing the top 215 of percentage correct (at 77 percent). Additionally, by initially training with entity attributes it seems as though this model learns in ways that are more similar to human learning. It maps raw data to attributes and associates entities that have similar attributes. It is very interesting to see that the taxonomic organization that we observed with initially symbolic (entity-relation-attribute) analysis had similar results when using raw data.


Some extensions that could be done to further explore this area are: (1) utilizing datasets with larger class sets to determine if size impacts the taxonomic organization (2) using a different set of entity attributes (3) Seeing if a trained attribute model can generalize well to other classification datasets (4) Seeing if a trained attribute model is useful as a base for transfer learning on other computer vision tasks. There are many more ways this project can be expanded and I'm hoping that those who have read this will be inspired to explore the possibilities.


The area of semantic cognition in cognitive science (and cognitive science in general) has a lot to offer the field of AI. The inductive biases introduced in the form of handcrafted features could lead to more robust, human like, and explainable AI algorithms.
